                        p.text-muted
                            |OGC API - Records supports a number of deployment patterns for catalogs.
                        p.text-muted
                            | The 
                            i crawlable catalog 
                            | involves creating static metadata files along with the data, in a web accessible location (e.g.: S3 bucket).
                            | At top-level, there should be a file to provide information about the catalog, including links to navigate through the metadata records.
                        .text-center.text-muted
                            img(src='assets/img/crawlable_catalogue_example.png', alt='...', style='width:40%', title='Generated with AI ∙ 6 August 2024 at 0:39 pm')
                        p.text-muted
                            | Although only providing visibility and navigation, the crawlable catalog comes with a very low implementation burden, and it can be low hanging fruit in terms of organising directories full of files (e.g.: EO images).  
                            | In terms of data discovery, creating a crawlable catalog is certainly better than having no catalog.
                        p.text-muted
                            | The 
                            i searchable catalog 
                            | also allows accessing collection level metadata and the individual metadata records, but unlike the crawlable catalog, it enables clients to filter the response with query parameters.
                            | This searching capability requires the metadata to be stored in a SQL or NoSQL database that can provide the querying functionality, so the simple setup using files on a web accessible folder is no longer possible.
                    .col-md-6
                        p.text-muted
                            | These are some real-life examples of querying patterns that can be used in a searchable catalog. 
